"# Chapter 15 — Stacking blocks and tokenization

Two final pieces before chapter 16 assembles the tiny LLM.

**Stacking.** A single transformer block is one 'floor' of the tower.
Real models stack many blocks — 12 for BERT-base, 96 for GPT-3. This
chapter shows how to stack them and why deeper is usually better up
to a point.

**Tokenization.** Whitespace tokenization (chapter 11) is fine for
demonstration but fails at scale — rare words become 'unknown,'
compound words don't split, punctuation is a mess. Real language
models use subword tokenization. The most common algorithm is Byte
Pair Encoding (BPE), which we build here in a small form.

## Stacking blocks

Stacking is just function composition. Each block takes a sequence
of vectors and returns a sequence of vectors of the same shape.
Compose them.

```
(define (stacked-transformer blocks embeddings)
  (fold (lambda (block acc) (block acc))
        embeddings
        blocks))
```

`blocks` is a list of block functions. Each is a closure over its
own weights. We fold — apply them one at a time in sequence.

## Problem 1 — Two stacked blocks

Not runnable end-to-end here because the block functions need many
weight matrices, but the shape.

```
;; Assume make-block builds a full transformer block (chapter 13) as
;; a closure. Then stacking is trivial.

(define block1 (make-block ...weights1...))
(define block2 (make-block ...weights2...))
(define block3 (make-block ...weights3...))

(define transformer
  (lambda (embeddings)
    (block3 (block2 (block1 embeddings)))))

;; Or as a fold:
(define transformer
  (lambda (embeddings)
    (fold (lambda (b acc) (b acc))
          embeddings
          (list block1 block2 block3))))
```

Read the shape. The output of block1 becomes the input to block2.
Same for block2 → block3. Since blocks preserve the (seq_len,
embed_dim) shape, they can be stacked arbitrarily.

## Why deeper helps

Each block can mix information across positions ONCE (in its
attention layer) and transform per-position ONCE (in its feed-forward
layer). With more blocks, information can flow further and be
transformed more times.

Empirically: a 1-block transformer is decent at short local patterns.
A 12-block transformer is much better at longer-range dependencies. A
96-block transformer can hold context over thousands of tokens. This
is one reason GPT-3 was so much more capable than smaller models.

More depth = more compute per token, more parameters to train, more
data required. Depth is not free. The sweet spot depends on data
budget and hardware.

## Tokenization — beyond whitespace

Whitespace tokenization has three problems:

1. **Vocabulary explosion.** Every distinct word is a distinct token.
   In English there are hundreds of thousands of distinct words if you
   count all forms and typos.

2. **Unknown words.** Any word not seen during training becomes an
   [UNK] token. Rare technical terms, new slang, foreign names — all
   [UNK].

3. **Morphology loss.** 'run,' 'runs,' 'running' are three separate
   tokens with no shared representation. The model has to learn each
   independently.

Subword tokenization fixes all three. Common words stay whole. Rare
words split into pieces. New words are ALWAYS representable as a
sequence of subword pieces.

## Byte Pair Encoding (BPE) — the algorithm

Sennrich et al. 2015 adapted BPE (originally a compression algorithm)
for text tokenization. The idea:

1. Start with a vocabulary of individual characters.
2. Count all pairs of adjacent tokens in the training corpus.
3. Find the most common pair. Merge it into a new token.
4. Repeat until vocabulary reaches desired size.

At tokenization time you apply the merges in the same order.

## Problem 2 — BPE training on a tiny corpus

Build a mini-BPE trainer. Not efficient — pedagogical.

```
(define (split-word s)
  ;; 'cat' -> ('c' 'a' 't' '</w>')
  (append
    (map (lambda (i) (string (string-ref s i)))
         (iota (string-length s)))
    (list \"</w>\")))

(define corpus
  (list \"cat\" \"cats\" \"car\" \"cars\" \"bar\" \"bat\"))

(define pieces
  (map split-word corpus))
;; -> ((c a t </w>) (c a t s </w>) (c a r </w>) ...)

(define (pairs-in tokens)
  ;; return list of adjacent pairs
  (if (or (null? tokens) (null? (cdr tokens)))
      '()
      (cons (list (car tokens) (cadr tokens))
            (pairs-in (cdr tokens)))))

(define (count-pairs word-lists)
  (define all-pairs (apply append (map pairs-in word-lists)))
  ;; return an alist pair -> count
  (fold (lambda (p acc)
          (let ((existing (assoc p acc)))
            (if existing
                (map (lambda (e) (if (equal? (car e) p)
                                     (cons p (+ (cdr e) 1))
                                     e)) acc)
                (cons (cons p 1) acc))))
        '()
        all-pairs))

(define (max-pair counts)
  (car (fold (lambda (e best) (if (> (cdr e) (cdr best)) e best))
             (car counts) (cdr counts))))

(display (max-pair (count-pairs pieces)))
;; => the most common pair, e.g. (\"c\" \"a\") -- because c and a appear
;; adjacent in cat, cats, car, cars.
```

Given the most common pair, we merge it. Every occurrence of that
pair in the corpus becomes a single token. Then we recount and
repeat.

## Problem 3 — Apply a merge

```
(define (apply-merge pair word)
  ;; Replace every occurrence of the pair with the merged token
  (define merged (string-append (car pair) (cadr pair)))
  (let loop ((rem word) (out '()))
    (cond ((null? rem) (reverse out))
          ((and (pair? rem) (pair? (cdr rem))
                (equal? (car rem) (car pair))
                (equal? (cadr rem) (cadr pair)))
           (loop (cddr rem) (cons merged out)))
          (else (loop (cdr rem) (cons (car rem) out))))))

(display (apply-merge (list \"c\" \"a\")
                      (list \"c\" \"a\" \"t\" \"</w>\")))
;; => (\"ca\" \"t\" \"</w>\")
```

After the merge, 'ca' is one token. Now we can find the next most
common pair — probably (ca t) — and merge again to get 'cat.' After
enough merges, common English words are single tokens; rare words
split into subword pieces.

## Problem 4 — BPE training loop

Put it together. Train BPE to build a vocabulary of size N.

```
(define (train-bpe corpus target-vocab-size)
  ;; corpus: list of words (strings)
  ;; return: list of merges applied in order
  (let loop ((pieces (map split-word corpus))
             (merges '())
             (n 0))
    (if (>= n target-vocab-size)
        (reverse merges)
        (let* ((counts (count-pairs pieces))
               (best (if (null? counts) #f (max-pair counts))))
          (if (or (not best) (null? counts))
              (reverse merges)
              (loop (map (lambda (word) (apply-merge best word)) pieces)
                    (cons best merges)
                    (+ n 1)))))))

(display (train-bpe (list \"cat\" \"cats\" \"car\" \"cars\") 5))
;; => a list of ~5 merges, ordered by count
;; e.g. ((\"c\" \"a\") (\"ca\" \"t\") (\"ca\" \"r\") ...)
```

The merges are stored in ORDER. At tokenization time we apply them
in the same order. That way 'ca' is always merged before 'cat,'
which is important for consistency.

## Problem 5 — Tokenize with a trained BPE

Given a word and a list of merges, apply the merges in order.

```
(define (tokenize-bpe merges word)
  (let loop ((tokens (split-word word)) (rest merges))
    (if (null? rest)
        tokens
        (loop (apply-merge (car rest) tokens) (cdr rest)))))
```

Feed a new word (never seen in training), and BPE produces a
tokenization — always representable because character-level tokens
are in the base vocabulary.

## For our tiny LLM

BPE is overkill for chapter 16. Our tiny LLM will use a fixed
whitespace vocabulary on a very small corpus, because the goal is to
show the mechanics of the model, not to fight the tokenizer. In real
GPTs, BPE (or its close relatives WordPiece and SentencePiece) is
essential.

## Capstone — A stacked-block sketch for chapter 16

Preview the shape we'll assemble in the next chapter.

```
;; The plan for chapter 16:
;;   1. Fix a small vocab from a training corpus.
;;   2. Random-init: embedding table + positional encoding + N blocks + output projection.
;;   3. Forward: embed, add positions, run N blocks (with causal mask), project to vocab logits.
;;   4. Loss: for each position i, cross-entropy between logits[i] and token[i+1].
;;   5. Backprop through everything.
;;   6. Update.
;;   7. Repeat.

;; Sizes for a tiny model that fits in memory:
;;   vocab_size = ~30
;;   embed_dim  = 8
;;   ff_hidden  = 16
;;   heads      = 1
;;   blocks     = 2
;;   seq_len    = 8

;; Total parameters: probably < 10,000. Trains in seconds on a
;; short corpus.
```

That is the target. Small enough to fit in your head, big enough to
learn something.

## Why this matters

Stacking is the mechanism by which transformers get 'deep.' More
blocks = more transformation capacity = better model up to some
limit set by data and compute. Tokenization is how symbols enter and
exit the model — without a decent tokenizer, everything downstream
is corrupted. Both are foundational, both usually taken for granted,
both worth doing once by hand to see.

## What's next

Chapter 16. The tiny LLM. It uses everything from chapters 2-15. We
will build it, train it on a tiny corpus, and watch it generate
text. Not smart text — but recognizably text-shaped, produced by the
mechanics we spent 15 chapters unpacking.
")
